---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const meta = {
  title: "Building a Tier List Maker: A Technical Deep Dive",
  description: "Ever wondered how drag-and-drop ranking tools work under the hood? Discover the web APIs, state management, and architecture behind modern tier list applications.",
  category: "tool",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};

const schema = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the best library for building a tier list maker in React?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Currently, dnd-kit is widely considered the best drag-and-drop library for React due to its modularity, lightweight nature, and excellent accessibility support. Older libraries like react-beautiful-dnd are no longer actively maintained."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How do you save a tier list as an image using JavaScript?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The most common method is using the html2canvas library. It traverses the DOM of your tier list and redraws it onto an HTML5 Canvas element. You can then use the canvas.toDataURL() method to extract the image data as a Base64 string."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Why does html2canvas fail to render external images?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "This is due to CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing) restrictions. If the external image server does not provide the appropriate Access-Control-Allow-Origin headers, the canvas becomes 'tainted' to prevent data theft, and export methods will throw a security error."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How should I structure the state for a drag and drop application?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "A normalized state structure is highly recommended. Keep an object dictionary of all items by ID, and a separate object for tiers that contains arrays of item IDs. This flattens the state tree and makes drag-and-drop updates O(1) complexity."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is HTML5 native drag and drop suitable for tier lists?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "While possible, native HTML5 DnD is generally discouraged for complex applications. It suffers from inconsistent cross-browser behavior, poor mobile touch support, and complex event management compared to modern abstraction libraries."
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "Building a Tier List Maker: A Technical Deep Dive",
    "description": "Ever wondered how drag-and-drop ranking tools work under the hood? Discover the web APIs, state management, and architecture behind modern tier list applications.",
    "author": {
      "@type": "Organization",
      "name": "SiliconBased"
    }
  }
];
---
<SiteLayout site="siliconbased" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical="https://siliconbased.dev/tier-list-maker" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>{meta.title}</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">{meta.description}</p>
    </div>

    <div class="article-body">

    <h2>Introduction to Interactive Ranking Tools</h2>
    <p>A <strong>tier list maker</strong> is a web application that allows users to rank items—such as video game characters, movies, or programming languages—into discrete, color-coded categories (S, A, B, C, D, F). From a developer's perspective, building a robust tier list maker presents an excellent exercise in frontend state management, drag-and-drop (DnD) interactions, and client-side data persistence.</p>
    <p>While the UI appears simple, the underlying logic must gracefully handle complex user interactions. Users expect to drag items between categories, reorder items within a single category, and seamlessly add or remove tiers. Additionally, generating a shareable image from the DOM is a staple feature of these applications. In this deep dive, we will explore the architecture, web APIs, and implementation details necessary to build a performant tier list application.</p>

    <h2>The Architecture of a Tier List Application</h2>
    <p>At its core, a tier list maker consists of a pool of unranked items and a set of ordered rows representing the tiers. The application state must track the position of every item. A common approach is to represent the state as a normalized data structure. Instead of deeply nested objects, which are harder to update immutably, developers often use a flat dictionary of items and a dictionary of tiers.</p>

    <div class="card">
        <h3>Normalized State Example (React/Redux)</h3>
        <pre><code>
const initialState = &#123;
  items: &#123;
    'item-1': &#123; id: 'item-1', name: 'JavaScript', img: '/js.png' &#125;,
    'item-2': &#123; id: 'item-2', name: 'Python', img: '/py.png' &#125;,
    'item-3': &#123; id: 'item-3', name: 'Rust', img: '/rust.png' &#125;
  &#125;,
  tiers: &#123;
    'tier-s': &#123; id: 'tier-s', title: 'S', color: '#ff7f7f', itemIds: ['item-3'] &#125;,
    'tier-a': &#123; id: 'tier-a', title: 'A', color: '#ffbf7f', itemIds: ['item-2'] &#125;,
    'unranked': &#123; id: 'unranked', title: 'Unranked', color: '#eee', itemIds: ['item-1'] &#125;
  &#125;,
  tierOrder: ['tier-s', 'tier-a', 'unranked']
&#125;;
        </code></pre>
    </div>

    <p>This normalized structure allows the application to perform <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>O</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></math> lookups when moving an item from one tier to another. When a drag-and-drop operation completes, the application only needs to update the <code>itemIds</code> arrays of the source and destination tiers, maintaining reference equality for unaffected tiers to optimize rendering.</p>

    <h2>Implementing Drag and Drop Interfaces</h2>
    <p>Drag and drop is the defining feature of a tier list maker. Historically, developers relied on the native HTML5 Drag and Drop API. While powerful, the native API is notoriously idiosyncratic, requiring developers to manually manage event listeners for <code>dragstart</code>, <code>dragover</code>, <code>dragenter</code>, <code>dragleave</code>, and <code>drop</code>. It also provides poor out-of-the-box support for touch devices and accessibility.</p>

    <p>Modern frontend development heavily favors specialized DnD libraries that abstract away these complexities. In the React ecosystem, libraries like <strong>dnd-kit</strong> and <strong>react-beautiful-dnd</strong> (now deprecated in favor of libraries like Pragmatic drag and drop) are popular choices.</p>

    <h3>The Mechanics of DnD State Updates</h3>
    <p>When a user drops an item, the application must calculate the new state based on the source location, destination location, and index. There are two primary scenarios to handle:</p>
    <ol>
        <li><strong>Reordering within the same tier:</strong> The item is moved to a new index within the same <code>itemIds</code> array.</li>
        <li><strong>Moving between tiers:</strong> The item is removed from the source tier's <code>itemIds</code> array and inserted into the destination tier's <code>itemIds</code> array at the specified index.</li>
    </ol>

    <div class="callout">
        <strong>Key Concept: Optimistic UI Updates</strong><br/>
        For a fluid user experience, the visual representation of the dragged item should update instantly. DnD libraries typically handle this by applying CSS transforms (like <code>translate3d</code>) during the drag, avoiding expensive DOM reflows until the drop completes.
    </div>

    <h2>Exporting to Image: The html2canvas Approach</h2>
    <p>Once a user completes their tier list, they inevitably want to share it on social media or forums. This requires converting the HTML/CSS representation of the tier list into a static image (PNG or JPEG). The industry-standard tool for this client-side operation is <strong>html2canvas</strong>.</p>
    <p><code>html2canvas</code> works by traversing the DOM tree of the target element, reading all applied CSS styles, and meticulously redrawing the UI onto an HTML <code>&lt;canvas&gt;</code> element. From there, the canvas can be exported using <code>canvas.toDataURL("image/png")</code>.</p>

    <p>However, developers must be aware of several limitations when using <code>html2canvas</code>:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>CORS Issues:</strong> If the tier list uses images hosted on external domains, the canvas will become "tainted" and cannot be exported unless the server provides appropriate Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) headers and the image tags include the <code>crossorigin="anonymous"</code> attribute.</li>
        <li><strong>Unsupported CSS:</strong> Complex CSS properties, such as certain CSS grid layouts, box-shadows, or modern filters, may not render accurately on the canvas. Developers often have to provide fallback styles specifically for the export process.</li>
        <li><strong>Performance:</strong> Redrawing a large DOM tree onto a canvas is computationally expensive and can block the main thread, causing temporary UI freezes. For very large tier lists, this process must be optimized or offloaded.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Data Persistence and State Restoration</h2>
    <p>If a user accidentally closes their browser tab mid-creation, losing their progress can be highly frustrating. A robust tier list maker implements automatic saving mechanisms. The simplest approach is utilizing the browser's <code>localStorage</code> API.</p>
    <p>By serializing the normalized application state to a JSON string and saving it to <code>localStorage</code> on every state change (debounced for performance), the application can seamlessly restore the user's progress upon reloading. For more advanced implementations, developers might implement cloud saves by persisting the state to a backend database like PostgreSQL or a NoSQL solution like MongoDB, associating the tier list data with a user session or account.</p>

    <h2>Why It Matters: Educational Value of Tier List Mechanics</h2>
    <p>Building a tier list application is more than just creating a toy project. It encompasses fundamental concepts of modern web development. State normalization, complex event handling, accessibility in highly interactive widgets, and client-side image generation are skills directly transferable to enterprise software development. For example, the drag-and-drop mechanics used in a tier list are identical to those required for building a Kanban board like Trello or Jira.</p>

    <p>Furthermore, if you are interested in exploring other complex systems, check out our guide on the architecture of large-scale platforms like <a href="/angies-list">Angie's List</a> or how developers track media consumption in applications like a <a href="/one-piece-filler-list">One Piece Filler List</a> tracker.</p>

    <p>To deepen the understanding of how applications manage this kind of complexity, let's look closer at the event loop implications of drag-and-drop operations. During a continuous drag event, the browser fires `mousemove` or `pointermove` events at a high frequency (often tied to the display's refresh rate, e.g., 60Hz or 120Hz). If the application state updates synchronously on every single event, it can lead to massive layout thrashing and dropped frames. This is known as "jank". Modern libraries mitigate this by decoupling the visual representation of the dragged item from the actual state. The dragged item is often taken out of the normal document flow (using `position: fixed` or `absolute`) and its coordinates are updated directly via inline styles bypassing the React/Vue render cycle. Only when the drag operation concludes (the `drop` event) does the framework state actually mutate, causing a single, controlled re-render.</p>

    <p>Another crucial aspect is keyboard accessibility. Native HTML drag and drop is notoriously hostile to screen readers and keyboard-only users. A well-engineered tier list maker must implement a parallel interaction model. This typically involves allowing users to focus on an item using the `Tab` key, press `Space` to "pick up" the item, use the arrow keys to navigate between drop targets (tiers), and press `Space` again to drop it. This requires careful management of the `aria-live` regions to announce the item's current location and available actions to assistive technologies.</p>

    <p>Handling image assets is another area fraught with edge cases. When users upload their own images to use in the tier list, a naive implementation might base64 encode the image and store it directly in `localStorage`. However, `localStorage` has a strict size limit (usually around 5MB per origin). Uploading just a few high-resolution images will quickly exhaust this quota, leading to `QuotaExceededError` exceptions. To solve this, developers must implement image compression on the client side before storage, or utilize the `IndexedDB` API, which offers significantly larger storage limits suitable for blob data.</p>

    <p>In summary, the journey of building a tier list maker touches upon almost every pillar of modern frontend engineering: performance optimization, accessibility, robust data structures, and intricate browser APIs.</p>

    </div>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <details>
            <summary>What is the best library for building a tier list maker in React?</summary>
            <p>Currently, dnd-kit is widely considered the best drag-and-drop library for React due to its modularity, lightweight nature, and excellent accessibility support. Older libraries like react-beautiful-dnd are no longer actively maintained.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
            <summary>How do you save a tier list as an image using JavaScript?</summary>
            <p>The most common method is using the html2canvas library. It traverses the DOM of your tier list and redraws it onto an HTML5 Canvas element. You can then use the canvas.toDataURL() method to extract the image data as a Base64 string.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
            <summary>Why does html2canvas fail to render external images?</summary>
            <p>This is due to CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing) restrictions. If the external image server does not provide the appropriate Access-Control-Allow-Origin headers, the canvas becomes 'tainted' to prevent data theft, and export methods will throw a security error.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
            <summary>How should I structure the state for a drag and drop application?</summary>
            <p>A normalized state structure is highly recommended. Keep an object dictionary of all items by ID, and a separate object for tiers that contains arrays of item IDs. This flattens the state tree and makes drag-and-drop updates O(1) complexity.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
            <summary>Is HTML5 native drag and drop suitable for tier lists?</summary>
            <p>While possible, native HTML5 DnD is generally discouraged for complex applications. It suffers from inconsistent cross-browser behavior, poor mobile touch support, and complex event management compared to modern abstraction libraries.</p>
        </details>
    </section>
  </div>
  <style is:inline>
